 What threatens future growth instead, the authors argue, are the weaknesses of China's financial system that undermine efficiency in investment allocation. Financial-sector reform and development are necessary, not only for sustaining long-term growth, but also for maintaining macroeconomic stability. Although it includes some technical economic analysis, How China Grows is accessible to noneconomists and will benefit anyone who is interested in development finance in general and in China's economic growth in particular--whether economists, political scientists, bankers, or business people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFinancezChina. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh  a"as.  aAsian financial crisis.  aCao, Yuanzheng.  aChina Statistical Yearbook.  aEurope.  aFan, Xiaohang.  aGermany.  aH-shares.  aHong Kong.  aJohnson, Samuel.  aKaminsky, Graciela.  aKuijs, Louis.  aLevine, Ross.  aM2 measurement.  aN-shares.  aNaughton, Barry.  aSolow growth model.  aagriculture.  aasymmetric bonds.  abanks.  abond market.  acapital-labor ratio.  adecentralization.  adollar peg.  aelasticity.  afinancial sector.  ahousehold saving.  aimpossible trinity.  aindividual enterprises.  ainvestment.  aloans.  amigration.  apaper tigers.  apolicy banks.  aregression analysis.  aswap centers.  atax farming system.  aurban sector.1 aGao, Jian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJin, Jing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691220185zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978069122018542